What Is a Bull Barrel?

A bull barrel is a type of gun barrel that does not taper outward, making it completely cylindrical. This makes the barrel stiffer, which reduces the amplitude of the vibrations in the barrel created by by the sudden increase of air pressure in the chamber when the gun goes off. The point of the bull barrel is to reduce the negative effect these vibrations have on aim.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Antique COLT collection
postcontent:
I am selling  a 3 piece Antique COLT collection. Included are three very nice original examples of Early COLT double action pistols.

Number 1 is a .38 long caliber 1892 Colt "New Army -Navy"  with a 4 " barrel it is a large frame civilian model this particular weapon was oringinally nickle plated with brown "gutta percha" grips.  the grips are fully checkered and have COLT with the rampant COLT emblem in a circle.This is the Second issue model of Colts First swing out cylinder revolver and as such has the flat latch and  dual cylinder notches. The cylinder rotates COUNTER CLOKWISE on this model and wasn't changed until the next evolution of pistols to Clockwise rotation as is now  standard on Colt pistols. Patent dates on this revolver are Aug.5 84,Nov.6 88  Mar.5 95 ( month abreviations are Original)

Number 2 is a Police Positive(First Issue) in .38 New Police as determined by the final patent date on barrel. This weapon is a medium frame blued with a 6 '' barrel and black fully checkered hard rubber grips with COLT in an oval. This pistol also has the flat latch. This is marked on the frame below the "Rampant Colt" NEW POLICE.  Overall condition on this pistol is excellent ! Lockup is tight and bore is excellent, Grips are as close to perfect as I have ever come across!!  Both the trigger and hammer on this pistol are fire blued and are as new. Patent dates on this pistol read :Aug. 5 1884, June 5 1900, July 4 1905 (note the July 4th patent date)

Number 3 is a Pocket Positive (First Issue) in .32 Colt CTG. as determined by the final patent date on barrel. This weapon is a small frame pocket model with 3" barrel. The pistol has an overall very nice brown patina finish and is wearing a pair of handmade  stag grips. This is a round butt model and has the round knurled cylinder latch. The patent dates on this pistol read: Aug. 5 1884, June 5 1900, July 4 1905 ( note again the July 4th patent date)

 I am asking $2200 for all three pistols this is several hundred dollars less than individual book pricing!! I am not really interested in breaking up the set BUT if someone approached me with the rigt CASH offer I might consider it. I may be interested in a multiple trade + cash  for modern pistols. Please price your items when responding.
Thanks

A1 Length integral Stock (5/8" shorter than A2) with sling loop

External finish is excellent, with the receiver showing a slight bit more overall wear than the other parts. Overall, 95% finish. The stock is all original beautiful blonde laminate. This rifle has a cleaning rod and sight hood, along with a reproduction sling.

Ammo is 1956 Yugoslavian surplus 196 grain heavy ball on chargers. I have never had any issues whatsoever with this ammo in my M.48, it is PHENOMINAL stuff. This is probably the last of it out there, I haven't seen it in months. It is in its original boxes already loaded on the chargers from the Factory.
